a. instruct the MT to undertake the following courses of action:
i. prepare a Schedule of stratified presumptive income level every tax period to approximate the gross sales or receipt of each business classification and submit a representation to the SB to setup or institutionalize the use of the same;
ii. continue to regularly business examine the accounts of business establishments applying for business renewal to determine the truthfulness of the declared gross sales or receipts used in the computation of business taxes paid pursuant to Section 171 of RA No. 7160;
iii. tag all the aforesaid suppliers and contractors with underdeclared sales or receipts and be subject to examination of books of accounts to ensure the correctness of taxes, fees, and charges to be collected;
iv. require the collection of unpaid business taxes from various business establishments with unpaid business taxes prior to their closure/retirement to pay their taxes due based on the submitted Sworn Statement of Gross Sales or Receipts;
v. coordinate with the ME to identify the contractors who have the bunkhouses or other structures that may be considered as project office as a basis for the imposition of business tax;
vi. collect business taxes from outside contractors who engaged in business within the Municipality and applying the situs of taxation;
vii. instruct the personnel-in-charge of the electronic Business Permit and Licensing System (eBPLS) to adjust the system’s default setup with the provisions of its Revised Revenue Code to avoid inaccurate computation of surcharges and interests; and
viii. require the concerned taxpayers to pay at least business deficiency of ₱1,200,942.44 without prejudice to their legal right to file a claim for credit or refund of ₱33,233.70 collections erroneously paid surcharges and interests in accordance with the provisions of RRC;
b. advise the Designated BPLO to implement the following measures:
i. require the submission of complete documentation of the financial records from taxpayers and ensure that these records form part of their permanent files to easily verify the correctness of the assessments; and
ii. prescribe a standard format of Sworn Statement of Gross Sales or Receipts when applicable and require the business taxpayers to have it duly notarized upon submission; and
c. require the MT and the Designated BPLO to devise measures to validate the declared gross sales or receipts of establishments applying for business permits.

