We reiterated and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to require the (a) Inventory Committee and GSO to (i) conduct physical inventory of all PPE of the Municipality on or before January 31 of each year; 


(ii) reconcile the resultant inventory reports with the Accounting records;




(b) OIC – Municipal Accountant and GSO to (i) maintain complete PPE records such as PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards for the proper control and monitoring of the agency property and equipment; and


(ii) consider the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to improve the reliability of the PPE accounts;



(c) OIC – Municipal Accountant to be prudent in accounting the PPE accounts by recording the completed projects to proper PPE accounts; and

(d) GSO to issue ARE to accountable officers to establish accountability for issued PPE.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the (a) Local Development Council (LDC) through the Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDO) to consider the immediate reprogramming to other priority undertakings of projects that are determined to be unviable for implementation during the budget year;

(b) Bids and Awards Committee, BAC Secretariat and Municipal Engineering Office to be prudent in exercising their functions and ensure compliance with the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its RIRR and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 in all stages of the procurement process and project implementation; and

(c) Municipal Accountant to submit the requisite documents for further verification/validation of the transactions.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive take the following courses of action to ensure the effective implementation of the DRRM Program:
Regularly review the annual LDRRM Plan, evaluate the implementability of the programmed PPAs and revise or recommend for re-appropriation, thru the LDRRM Council and SB, if warranted;
Expressly include the GAD aspect in the LDRRM Plan and Budget;
Establish a monitoring and evaluation scheme on the implementation of the DRRM PPAs so as to immediately address any hindrances and/or delays; and
Ensure that the minimum budgetary and reporting requirements are complied.

8.21	We recommended that Management require the:
Municipal Accountant and the Property Custodian to reconcile the accounts for newly acquired PPEs;
Municipal Accountant to (1) draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) taking up the (i) record the costs of the on-going infrastructure projects based on actual accomplishments; and (ii) reclassification of the assets acquired for distribution and small tangible items to the appropriate inventory/expense accounts; and (2) continue to update the PPELC for all property accounts to support the recorded balances of PPE;
General Service Officer to (i) maintain complete and updated property cards per category of PPE; and (ii) report all obsolete and unserviceable PPE in the Inventory and Inspection Report on Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) duly signed by the Head of Accounting Unit, Inspector/Appraisal Committee and approved by Head of Agency or authorized representative, and submit the report to the Disposal Committee for proper disposition;
Municipal Budget Officer to recognize the obligation of the construction of infrastructure projects based on progress billings and accomplishment reports;
Inventory Committee to (i) conduct complete physical count of PPE; and (ii) prepare/submit the corresponding RPCPPE (with appropriate remarks on the condition and whereabouts of the PPE) to the Accounting, GSO and COA; and
Concerned officials and committees to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE Accounts Balances of the Municipality in compliance with COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
• require the Municipal Assessor to continually facilitate for the titling of the lots in the name of the Municipality and establish ownership over the lots;
• continually monitor the accomplishment of the Municipal Assessor to ensure that subject lots are titled at least within the year and that funds for the purpose is provided; 
• prepare adjusting entry for the reversal of the appraised value of the land located at Barangay San Jose (fish pond) amounting to P1,000,000.00; and
• require the Municipal Accountant to identify the land in the Special Education Fund for the fair presentation of the Land account in the financial statements as required under Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the OIC-Disaster and Risk Reduction Management Officer to prepare the:
a. Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances for In-kind Donations;
b. Report on the Receipt and Utilization of Cash Donations;
c. Report on the Receipt and Distribution/Issuance of Donated Relief Goods; and
d. Report on the Receipt and Distribution/Issuance of Donated PPE; and furnish the same to the NDRRMC, through the OCD, copy furnished the Audit Team within ten working days after the end of each quarter pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 2014-002 and 2020-009.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) to undertake the following courses of action:

require the Municipal Treasurer to submit copies of title of lots to the Accounting Office and Audit Team for proper recording and verification as to ownership of the property;

advise the Property Officer to (i) update the RPCPPE of Land acquired through purchase or donation with corresponding status of existence, ownership and book value; (ii) maintain Local Road Network Inventory Map and Property Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation of PPE accounts with accounting records;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) update record of Land Account and reconcile record with Property Officer for lots with TRN; 


(ii) prepare and maintain Local Road Network Ledger Card for the local road networks to facilitate tracing of balances and transactions as well as reconciliation with the General Ledger controlling accounts; and (iii) upon disposal, draw a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to derecognize the unserviceable properties from the Accounting books and Property Records; 

require the Disposal Committee to expedite the disposal process of unserviceable properties following the proper procedures for the disposal thereof; and

require the Inventory Committee to (i) conduct complete physical count of PPE to prove the existence of the municipal properties and facilitate the reconciliation of any discrepancies found; and (ii) prepare/submit the corresponding RPCPPE (with appropriate remarks on the condition and whereabouts of the PPE) to the Accounting, Property Officer/GSO and COA.

We recommended that management take the following courses of action; to wit:

direct the Inventory Committee to (i) conduct physical count of all inventories; 

(ii) prepare the corresponding RPCI; and 


(iii) submit the same to the Accounting Office for reconciliation with the reported inventory balances in the books and to the Office of the Auditor at least once a year, if semestral reporting is not feasible; 

instruct the OIC-GSO to prepare and submit to the Accounting Office the SSMIs for issued inventories based on actual consumption/issuance and adhere to the monthly submission of the said report for accurate recording of expenses and assets accounts for the period; and


Advise the Municipal Accountant to take up in the books of accounts the cost of ending inventories of accountable forms and drugs and medicines to adjust the Inventories and Government Equity account balances by ₱129,860.71 at year-end.

