We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

cause the immediate liquidation of the cash advances granted to LGU officials/employees. Cause the withholding of salaries or any money due the officers and employees with overdue unliquidated cash advances to compel its settlement;

ensure that the liquidation reports are submitted to the Office of the COA Auditor for review. The necessary documents must be attached therein, such as the official receipts, certificate of seminar/trainings completed, etc. Henceforth, introduce controls that would assure that cash advances are liquidated or reported as soon as the purpose of the cash advance is served; 

file the request for authority to write-off unliquidated cash advances to the COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, in case of death of accountable officer, if all the conditions and requirements provided therein could be complied; and 

file the appropriate case to accountable officials who still failed to account/liquidate their accountability despite demand letters previously sent to them in violation of Article 217 of the Revised Penal Code.

We recommended and management agreed to direct/instruct:

the Municipal Accountant to (i) transfer the financial assistance from various NGAs and trust collections from the General Fund to the Trust Fund books in accordance with existing accounting policy; 



(ii) trace the records/documents relative to the unaccounted balance and remit the same accordingly to the source agencies; (iii) coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer for the return of unused funds to the source agencies (SAs) or to the National Treasury, as the case may be; and (iv) scrutinize the completeness of supporting documents of claims before releasing the same for payment and prior to the recording of the transactions in the books of accounts;

the Municipal Treasurer to draw a check for the remittance of unutilized amount of all completed projects and the remittance of share to the DPWH;

the BAC and TWG to adhere to the documentary requirements in all stages of the bidding processes; and

 the Officer in Charge (OIC) of the individual BuB Project to immediately push through with the completion and cope with the timetable of the project to ensure the full enjoyment of benefits that could be derived therefrom by the constituents of the Municipality.

We recommended that management adopt the following courses of actions; to wit:

Continue to finance its priority development projects and limit disbursements exclusively on PPAs which partake the nature of capital expenditures pursuant to the policies and guidelines on the utilization of the 20% Development Fund under the DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017;

Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to (i) post the Invitation to Bid and other Notices in the PhilGEPS, in the Agency website, and in at least three conspicuous places in the Municipality to promote transparency and competitiveness in all aspects of procurement; and (ii) conduct pre-procurement conference;


